01:02:17.239 --> 01:02:20.592
Prof: What happened that
there's so--in America you have

01:02:20.592 --> 01:02:22.809
a soap opera once a week for an
hour--

01:02:22.809 --> 01:02:24.239
William Ryerson:
 Well some are daily.

01:02:24.239 --> 01:02:25.300
Prof: Some are daily?
 

01:02:25.300 --> 01:02:26.969
William Ryerson:
 Daytime.

01:02:26.969 --> 01:02:28.679
Prof: You see those too,
right?

01:02:28.679 --> 01:02:30.108
How is it that--is that the
standard mood in

01:02:30.108 --> 01:02:31.039
&gt;?
 

01:02:31.039 --> 01:02:32.393
William Ryerson:
 It varies all over the

01:02:32.393 --> 01:02:32.630
place.
 

01:02:32.630 --> 01:02:36.920
In Latin America,
its daily, daytime and

01:02:36.920 --> 01:02:38.239
primetime.
 

01:02:38.239 --> 01:02:41.260
In many countries it's twice a
week.

01:02:41.260 --> 01:02:43.882
Some are once a week,
but once a week is really not

01:02:43.882 --> 01:02:46.976
adequate because you have to
hold the audiences interest for

01:02:46.976 --> 01:02:49.702
a whole week waiting for the
resolution of the latest

01:02:49.702 --> 01:02:51.990
cliffhanger,
so we like to do a minimum of

01:02:51.990 --> 01:02:53.596
twice a week,
and some of them are three

01:02:53.596 --> 01:02:54.099
times a week.
 

01:02:57.199 --> 01:02:59.429
Yes.
 

01:02:59.429 --> 01:03:03.217
Student:  If you--if
you're like having a program for

01:03:03.217 --> 01:03:07.070
like two years how do you draw
people in and say it's halfway

01:03:07.070 --> 01:03:10.728
through the show or a quarter
ways, how do you continue to

01:03:10.728 --> 01:03:12.719
inspire the new audience?
 

01:03:12.719 --> 01:03:17.597
William Ryerson:  Well--
The question was how do we deal

01:03:17.597 --> 01:03:21.858
with people who are drawn into
the program halfway through a

01:03:21.858 --> 01:03:23.518
two-year soap opera?
 

01:03:23.518 --> 01:03:26.882
The answer is one of the
beauties about having several

01:03:26.882 --> 01:03:30.751
hundred episodes is you can have
a lot of discussion of what's

01:03:30.751 --> 01:03:33.480
gone on in the past by the
characters,

01:03:33.480 --> 01:03:38.570
so people who join the audience
partway through the two or three

01:03:38.570 --> 01:03:43.175
years that it might be on the
air learn a lot about it and

01:03:43.175 --> 01:03:47.456
they also may learn about it
from other members of the

01:03:47.456 --> 01:03:48.750
community.
 

01:03:48.750 --> 01:03:51.849
Particularly in countries where
we have very high listenership,

01:03:51.849 --> 01:03:56.820
like northern Nigeria,
our most recent measure was 82%

01:03:56.820 --> 01:04:01.510
of the adult population is
listening every week.

01:04:01.510 --> 01:04:04.909
There it's become a cultural
event,

01:04:04.909 --> 01:04:08.601
so people who are joining it
hear both about the program from

01:04:08.601 --> 01:04:11.972
their neighbors,
as well as hearing characters

01:04:11.972 --> 01:04:16.150
talking about the past and
getting caught up that way.

01:04:16.150 --> 01:04:19.554
One of the questions I'm often
asked and maybe I should wait

01:04:19.554 --> 01:04:22.730
until somebody asks me this
question is how do we decide

01:04:22.730 --> 01:04:24.518
what it is we're promoting.
 

01:04:24.518 --> 01:04:28.070
In a sense, what gives us,
as an American organization,

01:04:28.070 --> 01:04:31.557
the right to go into some
country and tell them how to

01:04:31.557 --> 01:04:32.150
live?
 

01:04:32.150 --> 01:04:37.231
Indeed, one of the things that
we've adopted as a strategy is

01:04:37.231 --> 01:04:40.789
looking at the policies of each
country;

01:04:40.789 --> 01:04:44.775
most countries are signatories
of the Cairo Program of Action

01:04:44.775 --> 01:04:48.762
on Population and Development,
and of the Beijing Platform of

01:04:48.762 --> 01:04:50.690
Action on Women's Rights.
 

01:04:50.690 --> 01:04:54.637
If they're a signatory of those
documents then part of their

01:04:54.637 --> 01:04:58.586
national policy is incorporated
in those documents which are

01:04:58.586 --> 01:05:02.668
really global agreements on the
rights and status of women and

01:05:02.668 --> 01:05:04.409
reproductive health.
 

01:05:04.409 --> 01:05:07.987
So, we use that as a starting
point as the basis for the

01:05:07.987 --> 01:05:10.980
values that will be promoted by
the program.

01:05:10.980 --> 01:05:15.480
Then the policies of the
country may add nuances to that,

01:05:15.480 --> 01:05:19.103
so when we go into a country,
we explain to them we are there

01:05:19.103 --> 01:05:21.460
to help them promote their
policies,

01:05:21.460 --> 01:05:24.510
we're not trying to impose
something from the outside.

01:05:24.510 --> 01:05:25.750
Yes.
 

01:05:25.750 --> 01:05:27.610
Student:  Well I was
going to actually ask how--do

01:05:27.610 --> 01:05:29.635
you find that you have a lot of
opposition from governments or

01:05:29.635 --> 01:05:30.400
other institutions?
 

01:05:30.400 --> 01:05:32.909
William Ryerson:
 Hardly any.

01:05:32.909 --> 01:05:34.994
William Ryerson:
 The question was do we

01:05:34.994 --> 01:05:36.579
have opposition from
governments?

01:05:36.579 --> 01:05:40.981
One of the things about this
strategy is, because we're

01:05:40.981 --> 01:05:44.568
working to support the
government's policies,

01:05:44.568 --> 01:05:47.829
they are very enthusiastic
about it.

01:05:47.829 --> 01:05:51.934
Second, we get very little
opposition from the public

01:05:51.934 --> 01:05:56.512
because of the very gradual
evolution of the characters and

01:05:56.512 --> 01:05:58.824
because,
by doing our homework and

01:05:58.824 --> 01:06:02.010
really understanding the culture
before we ever get started,

01:06:02.010 --> 01:06:04.340
and having writers from that
culture,

01:06:04.340 --> 01:06:06.409
all of our programs are
written, produced,

01:06:06.409 --> 01:06:08.889
and managed by country
nationals.

01:06:08.889 --> 01:06:12.639
We know what the taboos are and
we steer clear of those,

01:06:12.639 --> 01:06:15.679
so we're not there to give
people shock therapy,

01:06:15.679 --> 01:06:21.025
we're there to start where they
are and move in the direction of

01:06:21.025 --> 01:06:25.099
better reproductive health and
women's rights.

01:06:25.099 --> 01:06:29.760
We don't do it in a way that
creates backlash or opposition.

01:06:29.760 --> 01:06:30.840
Yes.
 

01:06:30.840 --> 01:06:34.559
Student:  The Twilight
books and Seventh Heaven,

01:06:34.559 --> 01:06:38.137
shows like that,
I was wondering if people say

01:06:38.137 --> 01:06:40.393
that they are--
they were made to promote

01:06:40.393 --> 01:06:42.487
things like abstinence and
Seventh Heaven was always

01:06:42.487 --> 01:06:45.010
doing 'don't drink,
don't smoke' episodes.

01:06:45.010 --> 01:06:48.384
I'm wondering how you think
they relate to the programs that

01:06:48.384 --> 01:06:49.300
you guys show?
 

01:06:49.300 --> 01:06:51.789
William Ryerson:
 The question is,

01:06:51.789 --> 01:06:55.849
with American shows like
Seventh Heaven are we--

01:06:55.849 --> 01:07:00.780
what's the comparison between
their strategy for promoting not

01:07:00.780 --> 01:07:04.954
drinking and driving,
or abstinence with the kinds of

01:07:04.954 --> 01:07:06.539
programs we're doing?
 

01:07:06.539 --> 01:07:09.389
The answer is,
there is some comparison.

01:07:09.389 --> 01:07:13.045
That is, producers and writers
of American Hollywood shows are

01:07:13.045 --> 01:07:16.641
members of society and they're
parents and they're very aware

01:07:16.641 --> 01:07:21.728
of some of the problems,
and sometimes they attempt to

01:07:21.728 --> 01:07:27.268
address issues in the context of
their program.

01:07:27.268 --> 01:07:32.219
We had Neil Bear as a speaker
at an event we did at Hofstra

01:07:32.219 --> 01:07:36.742
University about a month ago who
produces Law &amp;

01:07:36.742 --> 01:07:41.179
Order and also was a
producer of ER,

01:07:41.179 --> 01:07:45.489
and there are very intentional
efforts to use some of these

01:07:45.489 --> 01:07:48.239
programs to promote positive
goals.

01:07:48.239 --> 01:07:52.831
They tend to do so in one or a
few episodes as opposed to

01:07:52.831 --> 01:07:57.670
having a program that's designed
around a set of issues,

01:07:57.670 --> 01:08:01.597
so it tends to be briefer
mentions of these issues and

01:08:01.597 --> 01:08:05.750
sometimes they're done well and
sometimes they're not.

01:08:05.750 --> 01:08:10.478
Indeed, there are lots of
examples of entertainment shows

01:08:10.478 --> 01:08:14.871
in Hollywood like the Bold
&amp; The Beautiful

01:08:14.871 --> 01:08:19.854
addressing HIV/AIDS through a
character named Tony who finds

01:08:19.854 --> 01:08:22.220
out he's HIV positive.
 

01:08:22.220 --> 01:08:25.775
They got an 800 number from
Donna Shalala when she was

01:08:25.775 --> 01:08:29.466
Secretary of Health &amp;
Human Services that they could

01:08:29.466 --> 01:08:34.029
run after those key episodes for
people to call for information.

01:08:34.029 --> 01:08:38.229
That show generated more calls
to that 800 number than the

01:08:38.229 --> 01:08:42.721
60 Minutes' treatment of
HIV/AIDs and 60 Minutes

01:08:42.721 --> 01:08:46.985
has a much bigger audience,
but it was the emotional impact

01:08:46.985 --> 01:08:50.921
of Days of Our Lives that
generated a huge response by the

01:08:50.921 --> 01:08:51.658
audience.
 

01:08:51.658 --> 01:08:54.953
So, some of these have been
very useful interventions,

01:08:54.953 --> 01:08:58.310
but they're quite different in
terms of methodology.

01:08:58.310 --> 01:08:59.560
Yes?
 

