01:09:35.783 --> 01:09:37.689
not of the content.
 

01:09:37.689 --> 01:09:43.536
They stopped doing social
content broadcasting at Televisa

01:09:43.536 --> 01:09:49.279
in 1985, and the birthrate had
come down dramatically.

01:09:49.279 --> 01:09:52.068
It was the most dramatic
decline in birthrates of any

01:09:52.068 --> 01:09:55.123
developing country in the
twentieth century during the ten

01:09:55.123 --> 01:09:58.233
years Sabido's five family
planning soap operas were on the

01:09:58.233 --> 01:09:58.770
air.
 

01:09:58.770 --> 01:10:02.148
When they stopped,
the birthrate plateaued,

01:10:02.148 --> 01:10:04.399
but it did not go back up.
 

01:10:04.399 --> 01:10:09.431
However, our view is because
there are new generations coming

01:10:09.431 --> 01:10:13.435
along every year,
and because people continue to

01:10:13.435 --> 01:10:17.546
need information on a whole
range of health and social

01:10:17.546 --> 01:10:20.413
issues,
these programs should be seen

01:10:20.413 --> 01:10:22.430
as a long-term intervention.
 

01:10:22.430 --> 01:10:25.997
We shouldn't say do a program
for three years and then walk

01:10:25.997 --> 01:10:27.679
away,
in the same way that we

01:10:27.679 --> 01:10:30.988
wouldn't open a clinic for three
years and then close it down and

01:10:30.988 --> 01:10:33.420
hope that the birthrate wouldn't
go back up.

01:10:33.420 --> 01:10:36.550
We really see this as a long
term intervention,

01:10:36.550 --> 01:10:40.198
but the evidence that we have
is probably not conclusive,

01:10:40.198 --> 01:10:45.314
but it appears that these
programs lead to permanent

01:10:45.314 --> 01:10:47.119
change in norms.
 

01:10:47.119 --> 01:10:48.010
Yes?
 

01:10:48.010 --> 01:10:50.779
Student:  Do you ever
find yourself at a competitive

01:10:50.779 --> 01:10:53.213
disadvantage to the more
traditional commercial soap

01:10:53.213 --> 01:10:53.738
operas?
 

01:10:53.738 --> 01:10:56.840
William Ryerson:
 Certainly in countries

01:10:56.840 --> 01:10:59.939
that have a mature media market
like India,

01:10:59.939 --> 01:11:03.243
like Brazil,
we are adopting more a strategy

01:11:03.243 --> 01:11:08.161
of working with the producers of
existing programs than trying to

01:11:08.161 --> 01:11:10.618
produce our own and compete.
 

01:11:10.618 --> 01:11:14.265
In Brazil, for example,
we're working in partnership

01:11:14.265 --> 01:11:18.270
with the social merchandising
department of TV Globo,

01:11:18.270 --> 01:11:22.140
which controls 65% of the
Brazilian audience.

01:11:22.140 --> 01:11:26.067
That strategy--actually their
department emerged because of

01:11:26.067 --> 01:11:29.655
the partnership we formed
originally through a meeting

01:11:29.655 --> 01:11:33.650
David Poindexter and I had with
Roberto Murino who owned the

01:11:33.650 --> 01:11:37.578
network and it was being done
through the product placement

01:11:37.578 --> 01:11:38.729
division.
 

01:11:38.729 --> 01:11:42.131
But ultimately they set up a
whole division to promote social

01:11:42.131 --> 01:11:45.936
causes through the telenovelas,
and so we helped them do that

01:11:45.936 --> 01:11:47.750
and we measure the effects.
 

01:11:47.750 --> 01:11:51.320
For example,
36% of the women at Planned

01:11:51.320 --> 01:11:56.634
Parenthood clinics in Brazil
were there because of one soap

01:11:56.634 --> 01:12:01.579
opera we evaluated called
Paginas Da Vida,

01:12:01.579 --> 01:12:05.750
Pages of Life.
 

01:12:05.750 --> 01:12:07.470
It's similar to what we're
doing in Hollywood.

01:12:07.470 --> 01:12:10.510
We're not--We may do a You Tube
soap opera,

01:12:10.510 --> 01:12:14.288
but we're not likely to get
ourselves on the air on CBS,

01:12:14.288 --> 01:12:20.247
so we're instead focusing on
working with writers of existing

01:12:20.247 --> 01:12:21.340
programs.
 

01:12:21.340 --> 01:12:23.198
Yes?
 

01:12:23.198 --> 01:12:26.050
Student:  I'm curious
about the range of social issues

01:12:26.050 --> 01:12:27.000
of your audiences.
 

01:12:27.000 --> 01:12:29.654
I mean if they're writing into
the characters and addressing

01:12:29.654 --> 01:12:31.408
them by name and giving
suggestions,

01:12:31.408 --> 01:12:33.430
they may not be so savvy about
the media,

01:12:33.430 --> 01:12:39.609
I'm wondering if that helps or
hinders your project or both?

01:12:39.609 --> 01:12:43.447
William Ryerson:
 It's a question that we

01:12:43.447 --> 01:12:47.529
try to understand before we ever
go on the air,

01:12:47.529 --> 01:12:51.430
what are their attitudes,
perceptions of,

01:12:51.430 --> 01:12:56.010
and consumption of
entertainment media.

01:12:56.010 --> 01:12:59.060
Indeed, the audience is,
in terms of their

01:12:59.060 --> 01:13:03.676
sophistication and their media
savvy varied dramatically from a

01:13:03.676 --> 01:13:07.100
place like Ethiopia to a place
like India.

01:13:07.100 --> 01:13:13.010
There's no one generalization,
but there are many stories

01:13:13.010 --> 01:13:16.810
about our experiences in
Ethiopia.

01:13:16.810 --> 01:13:19.302
For example,
the actress who played the

01:13:19.302 --> 01:13:23.109
positive female role model
Furkurta in that first program I

01:13:23.109 --> 01:13:26.623
was talking about,
went into a vegetable market

01:13:26.623 --> 01:13:30.420
and women recognized her voice
from the radio show,

01:13:30.420 --> 01:13:33.520
and one of them said you're
Furkurta and she said,

01:13:33.520 --> 01:13:34.907
well not really,
and they said no,

01:13:34.907 --> 01:13:36.832
no,
no we know you're Furkurta,

01:13:36.832 --> 01:13:39.560
we recognize you from Yeken
Kignit,

01:13:39.560 --> 01:13:42.765
and one of them said,
I named my baby daughter after

01:13:42.765 --> 01:13:46.350
you in hopes that she would be
as wonderful as you are.

01:13:46.350 --> 01:13:50.055
Clearly there--they are not
seeing the distinction between

01:13:50.055 --> 01:13:52.832
fantasy and reality,
but on the other hand,

01:13:52.832 --> 01:13:56.390
how many times have you heard
this about American audiences?

01:13:56.390 --> 01:14:00.404
It's hard to know really,
but clearly,

01:14:00.404 --> 01:14:05.938
probably the lack of
sophistication leads to greater

01:14:05.938 --> 01:14:11.579
influence of the programs but
it's hard to know.

01:14:11.579 --> 01:14:13.100
One more question.
 

01:14:13.100 --> 01:14:15.814
Student:  How do you
feel applying those models to

01:14:15.814 --> 01:14:18.529
other social issues such as
environmental degradation?

01:14:18.529 --> 01:14:21.435
Because it--I mean family
planning is really based on

01:14:21.435 --> 01:14:24.731
family relationships and how
people relate to each other and

01:14:24.731 --> 01:14:27.962
how do you see--
I guess how do you--what's your

01:14:27.962 --> 01:14:32.050
belief of what the success rate
of these programs will be--

01:14:32.050 --> 01:14:35.193
if it's more on environment
issues or other type of social

01:14:35.193 --> 01:14:35.800
justices?
 

01:14:35.800 --> 01:14:38.208
William Ryerson:
 The question is how do we

01:14:38.208 --> 01:14:41.355
feel about applying the strategy
to other issues like environment

01:14:41.355 --> 01:14:44.158
as opposed to family life and
family planning issues?

01:14:44.158 --> 01:14:46.399
The answer is we feel great
about it,

01:14:46.399 --> 01:14:51.109
however, you point out it might
not be the most exciting soap

01:14:51.109 --> 01:14:54.328
opera to do a soap opera on
recycling,

01:14:54.328 --> 01:14:57.786
so it doesn't have the same sex
appeal or audience appeal as a

01:14:57.786 --> 01:15:01.770
program about people's lives,
so we mix issues and we like to

01:15:01.770 --> 01:15:04.500
do programs about life in the
country.

01:15:04.500 --> 01:15:07.786
In the eastern Caribbean,
the nine countries where we're

01:15:07.786 --> 01:15:11.221
broadcasting a program,
that program is addressing both

01:15:11.221 --> 01:15:14.743
family planning and preservation
of the rain forests of the

01:15:14.743 --> 01:15:16.020
eastern Caribbean.
 

01:15:16.020 --> 01:15:18.920
In Rwanda, similarly.
 

01:15:18.920 --> 01:15:22.213
We're planning a program in
Papua New Guinea that will

01:15:22.213 --> 01:15:26.130
address conservation of marine
resources and family planning.

01:15:26.130 --> 01:15:31.908
Clearly, family life issues are
a perfect subject for melodrama.

01:15:31.908 --> 01:15:36.155
You have to be very careful how
much conservation kinds of

01:15:36.155 --> 01:15:41.453
content you put into a program,
but indeed, you can have the

01:15:41.453 --> 01:15:45.010
life of a village in a soap
opera,

01:15:45.010 --> 01:15:48.105
and for example,
in Papua, New Guinea one of the

01:15:48.105 --> 01:15:51.860
fishing practices that is
clearly a short term strategy is

01:15:51.860 --> 01:15:55.813
to use dynamite to blow up the
reef and it stuns all the fish

01:15:55.813 --> 01:15:58.908
and they can scoop them out of
the ocean.

01:15:58.908 --> 01:16:01.630
That's not a sustainable
livelihood,

01:16:01.630 --> 01:16:05.728
so we can demonstrate that
through a two year soap opera in

01:16:05.728 --> 01:16:10.109
a way that might take many more
years and be devastating to the

01:16:10.109 --> 01:16:15.182
marine environment if it--
if people just wait until

01:16:15.182 --> 01:16:17.310
they're starving.
 

01:16:17.310 --> 01:16:21.358
The point is well taken,
it's something where we have to

01:16:21.358 --> 01:16:25.257
be careful not to overload it
with messages and boring

01:16:25.257 --> 01:16:28.548
information,
it really has to remain an

01:16:28.548 --> 01:16:32.078
exciting program or we'll lose
our audience.

01:16:32.078 --> 01:16:35.268
Well I think we better call it
quits because we're past

01:16:35.268 --> 01:16:36.390
adjournment time.
 

01:16:36.390 --> 01:16:38.359
I thank you all very much.
 

01:16:38.359 --> 01:16:42.100
&gt;
 

